  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/actor/credibility-assessment-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z",
    "rationale": "The FEA model ensemble for non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw compression-bending has been assessed against all 13 ASME V&V 40 credibility factors at modelRiskLevel 5. Twelve of thirteen factors meet or exceed their required credibility level. The single shortfall — Test conditions (achievedLevel 3 vs. requiredLevel 4) — is addressed by the offset rationale below. All three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) satisfy the pre-specified acceptance criterion of E/uval < 1.96, with values of 0.61, 1.12, and 0.48 respectively. The multi-laboratory test program (N=11, two labs) and multi-solver ensemble (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) provide strong convergent evidence of model fidelity. The UQ analysis demonstrates that prediction uncertainty is bounded and well-characterized. The sensitivity analysis identifies Ti-6Al-4V tangent modulus and friction coefficient as dominant uncertain inputs, both of which are within experimentally characterized bounds. The package is assessed as fit for regulatory submission as part of the 510(k) credibility evidence package for the non-cannulated pedicle screw design.",
    "hasOffsetRationale": {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/offset/test-conditions-shortfall",
      "type": "OffsetRationale",
      "refersToFactor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/factor/test-conditions",
      "justification": "The Test conditions factor achieves Gradation 3 rather than the required Gradation 4 because validation testing was conducted under a single loading rate (5 mm/min) and single environmental condition (ambient dry), without a second loading rate or wet/physiological temperature condition. This shortfall is accepted for three reasons: (1) ASTM F1717 prescribes a single loading rate as the regulatory standard; testing at additional rates would not be representative of the submission scenario; (2) the quasi-static loading regime means rate effects on Ti-6Al-4V are negligible (< 0.5% QoI change per published strain-rate sensitivity data for this alloy); (3) the multi-solver ensemble and multi-laboratory design provide additional confidence that compensates for the single-condition limitation. The residual risk from this shortfall is assessed as Low given the regulatory context and the strong quantitative agreement achieved across all three QoIs."
    }
  },
